related_questions.question: Why did BlackBerry shut down?
related_questions.snippet: Why Did BlackBerry Smartphones Fail? Competition, in a nutshell. The introduction of the Apple iPhone, which BlackBerry didn't take seriously, caused a loss of market share that BlackBerry couldn't recover from. More competitors entered the smartphone space, eventually crowding BlackBerry out.

buttons.subtitle: Blackberry Phones History
buttons.title: BlackBerry | Definition, History, & Facts - Britannica
buttons.snippet: BlackBerry, any of a series of wireless handheld communication devices manufactured from 1999 to 2016 by the Canadian company Research in Motion (RIM; BlackBerry from 2013 on) that were among the first popular smartphones. The BlackBerry's roots go back to the RIM 850, a pager created by RIM in 1999.
snippet_highlighted_words: The BlackBerry's roots go back to the RIM 850, a pager created by RIM in 1999

buttons.subtitle: Date When Blackberry Was Introduced
buttons.title: First BlackBerry device hits the market | January 19, 1999 | HISTORY
buttons.snippet: On January 19, 1999, the first BlackBerry pager, BlackBerry 850, is released. BlackBerry devices go on to drive explosive growth for upstart Canadian producer Research in Motion (RIM), dominating the U.S. smartphone market for much of the 2000s. But they eventually lose their market share to Apple's iPhone.
